**Short answer:** The frontend can make the **panel feel slow**, but it’s probably not what makes the **project as a whole** slow (scraping, DB, fetch pipeline dominate that). The UI architecture is the main frontend bottleneck.

## What’s actually slow vs not

| Area | Frontend impact |
|------|-----------------|
| **Scraping / country fetch** | Almost none — subprocess + Playwright + ATS calls |
| **Panel load & interactions** | High — full-board re-renders + heavy API payloads |
| **Dev workflow** | Moderate — large unbundled JS files, no build step |

So if “slow” means typing in search, toggling filters, or marking jobs applied, the frontend is a real suspect. If it means fetch runs or Postgres migrations, look elsewhere first.

## Main frontend patterns that hurt performance

### 1. Full DOM rebuild on almost everything

The board is rendered with one big `innerHTML` assignment — every company card and every job row, every time:

```607:718:relocation_jobs/static/js/render.js
export function renderCompanies() {
  const list = $("jobs");
  const filtered = getDisplayCompanies();
  // ...
  list.innerHTML = filtered.map((c) => {
    // ... ~100 lines of HTML per company ...
    const jobsHtml = sortJobsForDisplay(c.jobs).map(renderPosition).join("");
    // ...
  }).join("");
}
```

That runs on search, sort, collapse/expand, show rejected/not-for-me, and after most job actions (`refreshJobBoard()` → `renderCompanies()`). There’s no virtualization, diffing, or incremental updates.

### 2. Search re-renders on every keystroke (no debounce)

```912:912:relocation_jobs/static/js/events.js
  $("search").addEventListener("input", () => renderCompanies());
```

Each keypress rebuilds the entire board. Search also scans all job titles per company on every render:

```182:199:relocation_jobs/static/js/render.js
export function filterCompanies() {
  const q = $("search").value.trim().toLowerCase();
  return state.allCompanies.filter((c) => {
    // ...
    const hay = [
      c.name,
      // ...
      ...(c.jobs || []).map((j) => j.title),
      // ...
    ].join(" ").toLowerCase();
    return hay.includes(q);
  });
}
```

With hundreds of companies and thousands of jobs, this gets noticeably janky.

### 3. Heavy HTML per job row

Each position is a large template (~15 buttons/badges/widgets). Multiply that by all visible jobs and you get a lot of string building + DOM parsing on every render. `render.js` alone is ~60KB.

### 4. Filters often trigger a full server round-trip

Most filters don’t filter client-side — they call `loadJobs()` → `GET /api/jobs`, which runs `flatten_companies()` + `compute_stats()` on the server. So “slowness when toggling filters” is often **backend + network**, triggered by frontend design:

```106:114:relocation_jobs/static/js/filters.js
async function applyFilterChange(def, checked) {
  // ...
  if (def.reload) {
    await loadJobs();
  } else {
    renderCompanies();
  }
}
```

Eight of ten filters have `reload: true`.

### 5. Large monolithic payload

The client keeps the full country in memory (`state.allCompanies`) and re-downloads it often. Each company includes `jobs`, `rejected_jobs`, `not_for_me_jobs`, tracking metadata, etc. As the catalog grows, both JSON parse time and render time scale linearly.

### 6. Asset weight (secondary)

- ~97KB CSS, ~360KB total JS (unminified, unbundled ES modules)
- Google Fonts loaded on every page
- 35KB `index.html` with lots of modal markup upfront

These matter on first load, but they’re secondary compared to full-board re-renders.

## What the frontend does *right*

- Fetch polling (800ms) only updates the header chip during active scrapes, not the whole board — intentional and sensible.
- Some job mutations use local bucket moves (`job-board.js`) instead of always hitting the API — but they still call `renderCompanies()` at the end.
- `loadJobs({ silent: true })` after fetch completion avoids the loading skeleton — small UX win.

## My overall read

**Yes, the frontend contributes to slowness** — mainly through an **all-or-nothing render model** and **tight coupling to a heavy `/api/jobs` endpoint**. It’s classic “works fine at 50 companies, gets painful at 500+” architecture.

It is **not** the reason scraping or the v2 fetch pipeline feel slow.

## If you wanted the biggest wins (rough priority)

1. **Debounce search** (150–300ms) — cheap, immediate improvement.
2. **Incremental DOM updates** — update one company card or one job row instead of `renderCompanies()` everywhere.
3. **Virtualize the company list** — only render visible cards.
4. **Move more filters client-side** — fetch once, filter in memory; server only for country/ATS/location changes.
5. **Paginate or slim the API payload** — don’t send full job objects until a company is expanded.

If you tell me where it feels slow (initial load, search, filter toggles, marking applied, after fetch completes), I can narrow this to the top 1–2 fixes worth doing first.

[REDACTED]

